      <exercise id="fs-id2392575" type="conceptual-questions"><problem id="fs-id3006575">
    <para xmlns:q="http://cnx.rice.edu/qml/1.0" id="import-auto-id3081359">What is the source of the energy emitted in radioactive decay? Identify an earlier conservation law, and describe how it was modified to take such processes into account.</para></problem></exercise>
      
      <exercise id="fs-id2397625" type="conceptual-questions"><problem id="fs-id2628800">
    <para xmlns:q="http://cnx.rice.edu/qml/1.0" id="import-auto-id1402635">Consider <link target-id="import-auto-id2600407"/>. If an electric field is substituted for the magnetic field with positive charge instead of the north pole and negative charge instead of the south pole, in which directions will the <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>α</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{α} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>, <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>β</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{β} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> , and <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>γ</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{γ} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> rays bend?</para></problem></exercise>
      
      <exercise id="fs-id2593990" type="conceptual-questions"><problem id="fs-id3007938">
    <para xmlns:q="http://cnx.rice.edu/qml/1.0" id="import-auto-id3104414">Explain how an <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>α</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{α} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> particle can have a larger range in air than a <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>β</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{β} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> particle with the same energy in lead.</para></problem></exercise>
      
